We want to know your thoughts regarding how statistics relates to your life. A lot of times, students only see statistics as useful because they want to get a good grade in it, or because they need to know it for a test. But the content you learn in statistics also can relate to your life in different ways. 

We asked students who took this course in the Winter and Spring 2022 term to think about how statistics was related to their lives. We want to know what you think about their responses. Your feedback will help us better understand students attitudes about statistics and help students who take this class in the future. Please rate the following quotations according to how interesting, relatable, and convincing you find them to be.

"Initially I did not understand how I could use statistics outside of this course. But when I started working in a non-profit organization I was able to use what I am learning here to visualize how funding was disbursed to the surrounding communities. My stats knowledge allowed us to identify which communities needed the most support."

How interesting is the quote to you?

You may remember at the end of Chapter 4 we asked you to rate students responses about how statistics was related to their lives. Here are three more student responses that we would like you to rate according to how interesting, relatable, and convincing you find the quotations. Your feedback will help us better understand students attitudes about statistics and help students who take this class in the future.

I never realized how relevant and applicable statistics was to my everyday life until I learned about modeling. For example, I have been trying to improve my mood and productivity since starting college by making sort of a mental model. I noticed that if I get enough sleep, get fresh air everyday, get some exercise in (even if its just a walk), and connect with my friends and family, my mood increases and I feel more productive. In this case, my mood/productivity is the outcome variable and sleep, fresh air, exercise, and social connections are possible explanatory variables.

How interesting is the quote to you?

I never realized how statistics is all around us. Understanding statistics helps us to better understand these claims, how data were collected, how the results were analyzed. If we don't understand the statistics behind the claims, then we can't use them to make good decisions (e.g., whether or not to buy an advertised product).

prompt:
We want to know your thoughts regarding how statistics relates to your life. A lot of times, students only see statistics as useful because they want to get a good grade in it, or because they need to know it for a test. But the content you learn in statistics also can relate to your life in different ways.
We asked students who took this course in the Winter and Spring 2022 term to think about how statistics was related to their lives. We want to know what you think about their responses. Your feedback will help us better understand students attitudes about statistics and help students who take this class in the future. Please rate the following quotations according to how interesting, relatable, and convincing you find them to be.

"Initially I did not understand how I could use statistics outside of this course. But when I started working in a non-profit organization I was able to use what I am learning here to visualize how funding was disbursed to the surrounding communities. My stats knowledge allowed us to identify which communities needed the most support."

How interesting is the quote to you?
Can you relate to this student's experience?
How convincing is the quote for showing you the usefulness of learning statistics and data science?

Before I came to college I thought that I would never use statistics outside of the required statistics course. But I quickly realized that statistics comes up in so many of my other classes. For example, a lot of the classes I take require some sort of paper and I have to read and interpret academic research. I also started as an undergrad RA in a research lab, and becoming comfortable with data analysis has been helpful in conducting my own research as well. This allows me to create various graphs and plots and sort through data.

How interesting is the quote to you?
Can you relate to this student's experience?
How convincing is the quote for showing you the usefulness of learning statistics and data science?

I never realized how statistics is all around us. Everyday we hear commercials about how "1 in every 5 Americans loves this shampoo" or how "this cleaning product is 85% more effective than others" or "a research study showed that." Understanding statistics helps us to better understand these claims, how data were collected, how the results were analyzed. If we don't understand the statistics behind the claims, then we can't use them to make good decisions (e.g., whether or not to buy an advertised product).

How interesting is the quote to you?
Can you relate to this student's experience?
How convincing is the quote for showing you the usefulness of learning statistics and data science?

Now, wed like to give you  the opportunity to reflect on the connections between statistics and your life. What would you tell another student about how what youre learning in statistics relates to your life? Be as descriptive as possible in the space below (aim for 3-5 sentences).

You may remember at the end of Chapter 4 we asked you to rate students responses about how statistics was related to their lives. Here are three more student responses that we would like you to rate according to how interesting, relatable, and convincing you find the quotations. Your feedback will help us better understand students attitudes about statistics and help students who take this class in the future.

I never realized how relevant and applicable statistics was to my everyday life until I learned about modeling. For example, I have been trying to improve my mood and productivity since starting college by making sort of a mental model. I noticed that if I get enough sleep, get fresh air everyday, get some exercise in (even if its just a walk), and connect with my friends and family, my mood increases and I feel more productive. In this case, my mood/productivity is the outcome variable and sleep, fresh air, exercise, and social connections are possible explanatory variables.

prompt:
We want to know your thoughts regarding how statistics relates to your life. A lot of times, students only see statistics as useful because they want to get a good grade in it, or because they need to know it for a test. But the content you learn in statistics also can relate to your life in different ways.
We asked students who took this course in the Winter and Spring 2022 term to think about how statistics was related to their lives. We want to know what you think about their responses. Your feedback will help us better understand students attitudes about statistics and help students who take this class in the future. Please rate the following quotations according to how interesting, relatable, and convincing you find them to be.

"Initially I did not understand how I could use statistics outside of this course. But when I started working in a non-profit organization I was able to use what I am learning here to visualize how funding was disbursed to the surrounding communities. My stats knowledge allowed us to identify which communities needed the most support."

How interesting is the quote to you?

For example, a lot of the classes I take require some sort of paper and I have to read and interpret academic research. I also started as an undergrad RA in a research lab, and becoming comfortable with data analysis has been helpful in conducting my own research as well. This allows me to create various graphs and plots and sort through data.

Understanding statistics helps us to better understand these claims, how data were collected, how the results were analyzed. If we don't understand the statistics behind the claims, then we can't use them to make good decisions (e.g., whether or not to buy an advertised product).
